item.description:
I used to think that simplicity is good because of the other values it often brings:
a simple system is easier to write;
a simple system is easier to build;
a simple system is more portable;
a simple system is easier to debug and reason about;
a simple system performs well;
a simple system is easier to change.
The word “simple” does some heavy lifting here, and I found that I would often use these as a metric for if something was simple or not.
In other words, these weren’t the result of simplicity, they were the definition.
